<main class="max-w-5xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">

  <!-- Header -->
  <header class="mb-12">
    <span class="text-orange-600 font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-sm">Unit 6</span>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-slate-900 mt-2 mb-4">
      Chemical Bonding & Nomenclature
    </h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-slate-600 max-w-3xl">
      In this unit, you will learn how electron behavior determines how substances bond
      and how chemical compounds are named.
    </p>
  </header>

  <!-- Essential Question -->
  <section class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-md border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-8">
    <h2 class="font-bold text-xl mb-2">Essential Question</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-700">
      How does electron behavior determine how substances bond and how compounds are named?
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ACCORDION SECTIONS -->

  <!-- Why Atoms Bond -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">1. Why Atoms Bond</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-slate-700">
      <p>Atoms bond to become <strong>more stable</strong>.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6">
        <li>Stability = full valence shell (usually 8 electrons)</li>
        <li>Bonding lowers potential energy</li>
        <li>Valence electrons determine reactivity</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Bond Types -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">2. Types of Chemical Bonds</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 space-y-4">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold">Ionic Bonds</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700">Metal + nonmetal → electrons are transferred</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold">Covalent Bonds</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700">Nonmetal + nonmetal → electrons are shared</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold">Metallic Bonds</h3>
        <p class="text-slate-700">Metals → sea of delocalized electrons</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Ions -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">3. Ions</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-slate-700">
      <p>An <strong>ion</strong> is an atom with a charge.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6">
        <li><strong>Cations:</strong> positive, formed by losing electrons</li>
        <li><strong>Anions:</strong> negative, formed by gaining electrons, end in <em>-ide</em></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Charges -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">4. Predicting Ion Charges</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 text-slate-700">
      <table class="w-full border border-slate-300 text-sm">
        <thead class="bg-slate-100">
          <tr>
            <th class="border p-2">Group</th>
            <th class="border p-2">Charge</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td class="border p-2">1</td><td class="border p-2">+1</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="border p-2">2</td><td class="border p-2">+2</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="border p-2">13</td><td class="border p-2">+3</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="border p-2">16</td><td class="border p-2">–2</td></tr>
          <tr><td class="border p-2">17</td><td class="border p-2">–1</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p class="mt-3">
        If the charge cannot be predicted, the metal requires a <strong>Roman numeral</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Polyatomic -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">5. Polyatomic Ions</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 text-slate-700">
      <p>Polyatomic ions are groups of atoms acting as one charged unit.</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6 mt-2">
        <li><strong>-ate</strong> = more oxygen</li>
        <li><strong>-ite</strong> = less oxygen</li>
        <li>Charge stays the same</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Ionic Naming -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">6. Ionic Compounds</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-slate-700">
      <p><strong>Writing formulas:</strong> balance charges to zero.</p>
      <p><strong>Naming:</strong> name the cation, then the anion.</p>
      <p>Use Roman numerals only when needed.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Acids -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">7. Acids</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 text-slate-700">
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6">
        <li>-ide → hydro– –ic acid</li>
        <li>-ate → –ic acid</li>
        <li>-ite → –ous acid</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- Molecular -->
  <details class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow border border-slate-200 p-6 mb-4">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg">8. Molecular Compounds</summary>
    <div class="mt-4 text-slate-700">
      <p>Two nonmetals → use prefixes.</p>
      <p>No mono– on the first element.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <!-- PRACTICE (HIDDEN BY DEFAULT) -->
  <details class="bg-slate-100 rounded-xl border border-slate-300 p-6 mt-8">
    <summary class="font-bold text-lg text-slate-600">
      Practice (Click to Reveal)
    </summary>
    <div class="mt-4 text-slate-700">
      <p>Classify and name:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc ml-6">
        <li>SO₂</li>
        <li>K₂S</li>
        <li>CF₄</li>
        <li>AlCl₃</li>
        <li>CuSO₃</li>
        <li>HI</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </details>

</main>

